Disease effect modeling using the lgpr package

Juho Timonen

2019-09-30

  • Basic non-stationary disease effect modeling
  • Modeling a heterogeneous disease effect
  • Modeling the uncertainty of the disease effect time

This vignette demonstrates how to use the lgpr package to generate artificial longitudinal data with a disease component and fit models with specialized disease effect modeling features.

library("lgpr")
# Loading required package: Rcpp
# This is lgpr (version 0.24.2)

Basic non-stationary disease effect modeling

First we demonstrate basic non-stationary disease effect modeling. We simulate data with 14 individuals, half of which are cases and half are controls.

# generate data -----------------------------------------------------------
set.seed(543)
simData <- simulate_data(N            = 14,
                         t_data       = seq(12, 96, by = 12),
                         covariates   = c(    0, 2,2),
                         relevances   = c(1,1,1, 0,1),
                         lengthscales = c(18,24, 1, 18,18),
                         onset_range  = c(40,60), # effect times drawn from this range
                         names        = c("diseaseAge", "sex", "location"),
                         t_jitter     = 1,
                         snr          = 5)

data <- simData$data
plot_simdata(simData, componentwise = T)

plot_simdata(simData, componentwise = F)


# create and fit a model --------------------------------------------------
fit <- lgp(formula = y ~ id + age + diseaseAge + sex + location,
           data    = data,
           iter    = 2000, 
           chains  = 1)
# * Interpreting 'diseaseAge' as the disease-related age variable.
# * Covariate 'sex' resolved to type 'categorical'.
# * Covariate 'location' resolved to type 'categorical'.
# 
#  ---------- LGPMODEL SUMMARY ----------
# 
#   Model:
#     f = f_1(id, age) + f_2(age) + f_3(diseaseAge) + f_4(sex, age) + f_5(location, age)
#     y ~ N(f, sigma^2*I)

#     - Identifier variable: id

#   alpha_categAge[1] ~ Student-t(nu=20,mu=0,sigma=1)

plot_components(fit)

PRED   <- lgp_predict(fit, X_test, samples = "mean")

plot_posterior_f(fit, PRED, n_sds = 2)

plot_posterior_f(fit, PRED, n_sds = 2, componentwise = TRUE)

Modeling a heterogeneous disease effect

Next we demonstrate disease effect modeling with heterogeneous disease effects. We generate the data so that only 2 of the 7 diseased individuals experience a disease effect.

# generate data -----------------------------------------------------------
set.seed(12333)
simData <- simulate_data(N            = 14,
                         t_data       = seq(12, 96, by = 12),
                         covariates   = c(    0, 2,2),
                         relevances   = c(1,1,1, 0,1),
                         lengthscales = c(18,24, 1, 18,18),
                         onset_range  = c(40,60), # effect times drawn from this range
                         snr          = 5,
                         N_affected   = 2,
                         t_jitter     = 1)

data <- simData$data
plot_simdata(simData, componentwise = T)

plot_simdata(simData, componentwise = F)


# create and fit a model with heterogeneous disease effect ----------------
fit <- lgp(formula      = y ~ id + age + diseaseAge + z1 + z2,
           data         = data,
           equal_effect = FALSE, # this option allows heterogeneous effects
           iter         = 2000, 
           chains       = 1)
# * Interpreting 'diseaseAge' as the disease-related age variable.
# * Covariate 'z1' resolved to type 'categorical'.
# * Covariate 'z2' resolved to type 'categorical'.

# 
#   Model:
#     f = f_1(id, age) + f_2(age) + f_3(diseaseAge) + f_4(z1, age) + f_5(z2, age)
#     y ~ N(f, sigma^2*I)
#   Variable types:
#     - Identifier variable: id
#     - Time variable: age
#     - Disease-related age variable: diseaseAge
#     - Other categorical variables: z1, z2
#   Likelihood: Gaussian

PRED   <- lgp_predict(fit, X_test, samples = "mean")
# * Computing predictions using posterior mean parameters.
plot_posterior_f(fit, PRED, componentwise = T)

Modeling the uncertainty of the disease effect time

Finally we demonstrate how to model the disease effect time of each case individual as an uncertain parameter. We generate data where the true effect times are drawn from onset_fun, but the effect becomes detectable only after a timepoint drawn from obs_fun. We fit two models, one using a uniform prior (p1) for the onset times, and one using an exponential prior for the difference of true and observed onset times (p2).

# define functions for drawing real effect time and observed onset
onset_fun <- function(){rnorm(n = 1, mean = 40, sd = 2)}
obs_fun   <- function(t){t + rnorm(n=1, mean = 20, sd = 4)}

# simulate data
set.seed(123)
simData <- simulate_data(N            = 14,
                         t_data       = seq(12, 96, by = 12),
                         covariates   = c(    0,2,2),
                         relevances   = c(1,1,1, 0,1),
                         lengthscales = c(18,24, 1, 18,18),
                         onset_range  = onset_fun, # true effect times drawn from this range
                         t_observed   = obs_fun, # time of disease detection drawn from this
                         snr          = 5)

data <- simData$data
plot_simdata(simData, componentwise = F)

plot_simdata(simData, componentwise = T)


# define priors and fit models -------------------------------------------

# Uniform prior for effect time
p1 <- prior_default()
f1 <- lgp(formula   = y ~ id + age + diseaseAge + z1 + z2,
          data     = data,
          prior    = p1,
          iter     = 2000, 
          chains   = 1,
          uncertain_diagnosis = TRUE) # this option allows uncertain effect time
# * Interpreting 'diseaseAge' as the disease-related age variable.
# * Covariate 'z1' resolved to type 'categorical'.
# * Covariate 'z2' resolved to type 'categorical'.
# 
#  ---------- LGPMODEL SUMMARY ----------
# 
#   Model:
#     f = f_1(id, age) + f_2(age) + f_3(diseaseAge) + f_4(z1, age) + f_5(z2, age)
#     y ~ N(f, sigma^2*I)
#   Variable types:
#     - Identifier variable: id
#     - Time variable: age
#     - Disease-related age variable: diseaseAge
#     - Other categorical variables: z1, z2
#   Likelihood: Gaussian
#   Disease component 
#     - Onset type: uncertain
#     - Effect type: homogeneous
# 
#  ---------- PRIOR SPECIFICATIONS ----------
# 
#   alpha_id ~ Student-t(nu=20,mu=0,sigma=1)
#   alpha_age ~ Student-t(nu=20,mu=0,sigma=1)
#   alpha_diseaseAge ~ Student-t(nu=20,mu=0,sigma=1)
#   alpha_categAge[1] ~ Student-t(nu=20,mu=0,sigma=1)
#   alpha_categAge[2] ~ Student-t(nu=20,mu=0,sigma=1)
# 
#   lengthscale_id ~ Log-Normal(0,1.151)
#   lengthscale_age ~ Log-Normal(0,1.151)
#   lengthscale_diseaseAge ~ Log-Normal(0,1.151)
#   lengthscale_categAge[1] ~ Log-Normal(0,1.151)
#   lengthscale_categAge[2] ~ Log-Normal(0,1.151)
# 
#   warp_steepness ~ Inverse-Gamma(9,5)
#   (sigma_n)^2 ~ Log-Normal(0,1)
#  
#  T_onset[1,1] ~ Uniform[lower=0, upper=96]

#  T_onset[1,3] ~ Uniform[lower=0, upper=96] 
#  T_onset[1,4] ~ Uniform[lower=0, upper=96] 
#  T_onset[1,5] ~ Uniform[lower=0, upper=96] 
#  T_onset[1,6] ~ Uniform[lower=0, upper=96]
